<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Gart Egilsson</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Heyokah<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2000<br />
	Location: Halas, Maine
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>If you can't see there has been a seismic realignment of players away from EQ, then you are deliberately blind.  <br />
<br />
I watched all the other games come and go without a blip on what I saw in EQ.  But EQ has been hemorrhaging in a truly remarkable way over the past few months.  The departures now are in fact different now that they were before.  <br />
<br />
Of current accounts for EQ, I wonder what number haven't logged in for the past couple of months?  What number have cancelled, but have time left on their subscription?  <br />
<br />
EQ will be around and folks will continue to play because it's got a lot of great things about it.  But they fugged up certain design elements so badly.  <br />
<br />
For me, the thing that really pissed me off was the continual effort to get spells.  After nearly 6 years, I've had it with that.  I loved the ritual of returning to Halas to get my spells and hanging out a bit.  <br />
<br />
PoP had too many crappy design elements and I think when all is said and done, did way more to hurt EQ's population than any other expansion - including Gates.  Gates was a nail in the coffin that is EQ's decline (but not demise), but PoP built it.  <br />
<br />
PoP was large and ambitious, and had a lot of great things about it, but the progression scheme/locked zone issue was always crap and the spell acquisition issue was always crap.  Ironically, I had fun in PoP eventually, but I think I'm objective enough to see that it splintered the player base in a really unhealthy way and essentially gave the finger to a lot of different play styles.  That's dumb, and it was apparent to me then, and it's even more apparent to me now.  Given this patch, it looks like SOE finally got the message too, sorta.<br />
<br />
Getting spells should not require raids or buying items from raiders.  It's that simple.  Even in a game with as large a raid focus as EQ developed as it went along.  <br />
<br />
By doing so, it told a significant percent of the population, "this is not for you".  They got the message and they left.  <br />
<br />
It did not have to be that.  Old EQ/Kunark EQ wasn't really like that.  I remember screaming about this on these boards and getting called a "whiner" "loser" and all kind of other perjoratives.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><br><br />
<a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=54513&amp;resize=true newwindow>Gart Egilsson</a><br />
