<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Gart Egilsson</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Heyokah<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2000<br />
	Location: Halas, Maine
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Well, although I do think EQ is starting a significant and permanent contraction, I don't think servers should be consolidated now.<br />
<br />
More chaos that that represents isn't a good thing.  There's simply a process of consolidation and recruitment that needs to occur.  Tons of family style guilds* crumbled after POP, and the uber guilds were loving life.  Now the uber guilds are crumbling left and right and they will have go through that same process of retrenchment and rebuilding (again and again for some).  <br />
<br />
And SOE should think even harder about backflag issues.  I don't know if this patch will address those completely or sufficiently.  Maybe.  If so, great.  If not, more people will quit who might otherwise not quit.<br />
<br />
<br />
* this is really a misnomer.  There were a lot of more casual guilds that raided some, but had a lot of members who didn't, or folks who came and went.  Raiding guilds can't operate really with that mix.  So powergamers who made the core of a lot of more casual guilds left, and many of them crumbled.  Those who didn't move through loyality or whatever, felt stymied in progression or they simply accepted it, or eventually (very eventually) flagged up through pickup/open raid schemes.  I was one of those guys who left for a guild that raided more.  My old guild is still around and doesn't raid at all.  Everyone I know is gone with a few exceptions, and most quit EQ completely.  I'm hijacking my own post...</p>
	
	
	
