<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Helfdane</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Mystic<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Dec 2001<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Tordail Farstryder</b><br /><i>People who succumb to the "teh sky r falling!!11!!1!!!" syndrome need to just take a step back and relax. A major holiday is coming in less than two weeks, not to mention a host of other online games have just come out. Wait for the dust to settle and things to calm down before you start passing around petitions about server merges. Besides, lower populations aren't necessarily a bad thing.<br />
<br />
/bow</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I reside on Karana with Tordail, and he and I have off again/on again had butted on several issues over the years, and I have to say this is going to be one of them again.<br />
Yes this is historically a lower population time for various reasons...college kids have gone home and are sans internet/computer, its hunting season in most states and while I would say that hunters are probably not a large portion of EQ's population, they are there.<br />
I could probably list a dozen other reasons why there are lower populations before I even began to hit on  EQ2 or WoW, but yes, they are reasons.<br />
Now, I am part of a small guild, very close knit, very friendly, but with very few real goals, just friends that enjoy playing a very good game. We rarely "raid" and when we do it is 1-2 groups hitting smaller targets more for fun and leg stretching than anything,  so the competition for higher end raid targets and such never really affected us. The vast majority of the guilds players are PM EST peak time players, and this is where I come in with the problem.<br />
Since I started playing EQ, I have always been a AM EST player, I log on at 9am EST after I get home from work (night shift ER nurse) and "relax" with EQ for 4+ hrs. For years this has been my daily routine, and I have learned to if not speak French, to at least be able to comprehend it, and have even over the years learned how to chomp my way through a smattering of German when that was necessary too. I also very very rarely raided...I work 4-5 nights a week from 8pm till 8am...not exactly condusive to raid time...and on my days off I spend my evening time with my wife and daughter.<br />
For the last 3 weeks though, EQ has been a technical graveyard for me at my peak times. I log on and LFG for 1, 2, 3, 4 hrs, soloing all the time, Factioning all the time, PLing alts, etc and rarely get a tell for a group.<br />
Now before this gets seen as a "oh woe is me" post, lets examine something here.<br />
I am a good shaman. I have main healed in MPG <b>BEFORE</b> I got the new 68 heal and I dont even have the GoD one. I routinely main healed in LDON hards before that. And yes, I was main/only slower in both those cases. I maximized my play time to be the best I could be given my limitations in both gear and no raid time. I had a fairly extensive list of people I regularly grouped with, either in MPG, LDON hards (before OoW), WoS, and Ruined City. Now, I sit routinely unable to get a group, thus I log off and play other games, tired of doing other than what I want to do (get to 70 before the new year).<br />
In my situation, server mergers may be a viable fix, allowing more people like me to actually see each other and thus get something done. I am a hard core non raider player, nearly 400 LDON wins, 275 AA, good and I sit collecting dust a large part of the time. How many people are in the same boat I am? How many have seen their peak time, because it is different from the normal peaks, become a quest to find a group let alone get anything done with that group. Would server mergers aid this? I think they would, but I think that the higher end players/raiders would not be happy.<br />
All I know is that something will be done eventually, but I fear that for the more casual, it may be too late, they have moved on to greener pixels.</p>
	
	
	
