<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Ragack</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jul 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>While I feel EQ will be going for a while and admit I wasn't around to see the effects of previous eqkiller releases. I think one thing people are overlooking is that this time it not a EQ killer it's a raid of them so to speak. EQ2 and WoW are the first of quite a few new MMORPG which will be competing for roughly the same players (though a few based on big properties will introduce new players). I think the problem will be that people will try one and if it is not for them head to the next new one instead of the game they must have already thought about quitting. I bet the longer it takes someone to think about coming back to EQ the less likely they will due to friends moving on.<br />
<br />
I some ways what I feel is happening to EQ is similar to what happened to Shamans. EQ attempts to please a wide variety of play styles and does a fairly good job (Like Shaman were fairly good at several roles). However most of the new ones seem to be after particular groups for which they offer more tailored game play which will be more likely to hold they interest (Like Shamans ended up lagging behind specialists in EQ to avoid becoming overpowered, thus were less desired).<br />
<br />
I can understand people wanting to hold off any merger decision till the dust settles, but if this series of new MMORPG's are released in a way that causes the dust storm to continue for too long, EQ could end up being buried in the dust.<br />
<br />
While I think mergers are too soon at the moment, I hope SOE is already forming plans incase, as I believe is likely, the returning masses never make it back.</p>
	
	
	
